<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="366" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,258,284]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is characterized by the forewing having an elliptical ochreous brown spot at basal 2/5 and on outer margin of cell respectively. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Wang &amp; Guan &amp; Wang, 2020" authorityName="Wang &amp; Guan &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2020" box="[826,969,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[826,969,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">S. purpurata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[976,1066,294,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[976,1066,294,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1913" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1913" box="[1123,1432,294,321]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stimulata">
<emphasis box="[1123,1255,294,321]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">S. stimulata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Meyrick, E." box="[1263,1432,294,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" pagination="136 - 141" refId="ref15844" refString="Meyrick, E. (1913) Exotic Microlepidoptera, 1 (3), 65 - 96. Marborough. Nagano, K. (1916) On a new micropterous moth from Japan. Konch Sek, 20 (4), 136 - 141." type="journal article" year="1913">Meyrick, 1913</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from them in the male genitalia by the sub-triangular cucullus straight on the ventral margin and the cornutus consisting of 12–16 denticles; and in the female genitalia by the corpus bursae with one elongate elliptical signum. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Wang &amp; Guan &amp; Wang, 2020" authorityName="Wang &amp; Guan &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2020" box="[383,524,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[383,524,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">S. purpurata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[531,620,402,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[531,620,402,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the ovate cucullus is obtuse on the ventral margin and the cornutus consists of six spines in the male genitalia; and the corpus bursae has one C-shaped signum in the female genitalia; in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1913" box="[151,282,474,501]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stimulata">
<emphasis box="[151,282,474,501]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="366">S. stimulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the sub-elliptical cucullus is obtuse on the ventral margin and the cornutus consists of 3–5 spines in the male genitalia; and the corpus bursae has two signa in the female genitalia (
<bibRefCitation author="Kasy, F." box="[998,1123,510,536]" pageId="8" pageNumber="366" pagination="227 - 299" refId="ref15655" refString="Kasy, F. (1973) Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Familie Stathmopodidae Meyrick, 1913 (Lepidoptera, Gelechioidea). Tijdschriftvoor Entomologie, 116 (13), 227 - 299." type="journal article" year="1973">Kasy 1973</bibRefCitation>
, P. 286, Figs 84, 86).
</paragraph>
